Coroutines provide more flexibility for time-based actions, such as executing code after certain delays or waiting for a condition to be met, while the `Update` method-based approach might be more straightforward for simple cases. Choose the approach that best fits your specific use case.

In Unity, you can wait for a coroutine to finish within another coroutine by using the `yield return StartCoroutine(CoroutineName())` syntax. This effectively nests the coroutines, pausing the execution of the outer coroutine until the inner coroutine completes.

Here's an example to illustrate how this works:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using System.Collections;

public class CoroutineExample : MonoBehaviour
{
    private void Start()
    {
        StartCoroutine(OuterCoroutine());
    }

    private IEnumerator OuterCoroutine()
    {
        Debug.Log("Outer Coroutine started");

        // Start InnerCoroutine and wait until it is completely finished
        yield return StartCoroutine(InnerCoroutine());

        Debug.Log("Outer Coroutine resumed after Inner Coroutine finished");
        // ... more code can follow after the inner coroutine is done
    }

    private IEnumerator InnerCoroutine()
    {
        Debug.Log("Inner Coroutine started");

        // Do something, wait for 2 seconds in this example
        yield return new WaitForSeconds(2);

        Debug.Log("Inner Coroutine finished after 2 seconds wait");
    }
}
```

In this example, when you run the `OuterCoroutine`, it will print "Outer Coroutine started", then start the `InnerCoroutine` and wait for it to complete. After `InnerCoroutine` has waited for 2 seconds and prints "Inner Coroutine finished after 2 seconds wait", the `OuterCoroutine` will resume and print "Outer Coroutine resumed after Inner Coroutine finished".

By using `yield return StartCoroutine(...)`, control flow in the `OuterCoroutine` is paused until the specified `InnerCoroutine` finishes its execution.

Keep in mind that `InnerCoroutine` could also yield on its other coroutines or asynchronous operations, making this a powerful pattern for sequencing complex behaviors. Remember to handle any cleanup or state management that might be needed if you stop coroutines prematurely using `StopCoroutine` or if GameObjects are destroyed while coroutines are running.
